    <title type="text">The Beginnings of Empire, 168-27 BC (Provincial Coins)</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a
      href="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/"><span
      id="current-site-header"><span accesskey="1" title="Beginnings of Empire Database home
      page [1]">The Beginnings of Empire, 168-27 BC</span></span></a><br
      /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span id="current-site-header"><span
      accesskey="1" title="Beginnings of Empire Database home page [1]"><img
      alt="http://d36jn9qou1tztq.cloudfront.net/static_site/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/banner.jpg.761215839307"
      class="decoded" height="46"
      src="http://d36jn9qou1tztq.cloudfront.net/static_site/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/banner.jpg.761215839307"
      width="200" /> </span></span></blockquote><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><b><span style="font-size: x-small;">The
      project</span></b><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">Work on
      provincial coins in the Roman Empire has demonstrated their potential to be used as a source to
      understand local culture as well as perceptions of the emperor and Roman power. The provincial
      coinage of the Republican period, however, has received little attention. By examining the
      iconography of coins struck by Roman officials and cities outside Rome in the period 168-27 BC,
      this project seeks to uncover how Roman power was represented, negotiated or rejected before
      the creation of the <a class="glossaryDefinition"
      href="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/glossary/?selectedLetter=P#principate"
      target="_blank" title="Click for more information">principate</a>.</span><br
      /><br /><a
      href="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/database/"><b><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">The database</span></b></a><br
      /><span style="font-size: x-small;">Another major aim of the project is to broaden
      access to and understanding of this material in disciplines other than numismatics.
      Consequently, the raw data generated by the project is being made available online for free
      public use. Users should note that the database only provides an overview of the iconography
      being struck in regions under Roman control; it does not list every variation and subtype. For
      these, users are recommended to consult the publications listed in the
      bibliography.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">This
      is an ongoing project. At the moment, the database has good coverage of Italy, Africa,
      Macedonia, and the coins struck by Roman <a class="glossaryDefinition"
      href="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/glossary/?selectedLetter=M#moneyer"
      target="_blank" title="Click for more information">moneyers</a> outside Rome as listed
      in Crawfordâ€™s <i>Roman Republican Coinage</i>. We plan to work on Achaea, Crete and
      Cyrenaica over the summer.</span></blockquote>&nbsp;<span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a
      data-page-url="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/glossary/"
      href="http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/research/dept_projects/beginningsofempire/glossary/"></a></span>]]></content>
